    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Style and culture of North American Indians who historically inhabited east-central California, western Nevada, and eastern Oregon. After 1840 a rush of prospectors and farmers despoiled the arid environment's meager supply of food plants, after which the Northern Paiute acquired guns and horses and fought at intervals with the trespassers until 1874, when the last Paiute lands were appropriated by the U.S. government. Today, the Northern Paiute are organized as several different federally and state-recognized tribes across California, Oregon, and Nevada.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000106006/NCSL, Federal and State Recognized Tribes (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>分布於加州中東部、內華達州西部、奧勒崗州東部之北美印地安族群的風格與文化。西元1840年後，探勘者與農民大量湧入，掠奪此地區有限的糧食植栽。之後北派尤特族取得槍砲和馬匹等物資，即與入侵者持續爆發零星衝突，直到西元1874年，派尤特族最後的土地也遭到美國政府占領。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
